338
00:20:07.012 --> 00:20:09.943
He wants this buckle. 500 a man.
one-handed match roping.

339
00:20:10.012 --> 00:20:11.632
10-Petal versus Dutton.

340
00:20:11.701 --> 00:20:12.805
[Zach]
Let's go now.

341
00:20:12.908 --> 00:20:14.218
- All right.
- [Zach] All right.

342
00:20:14.322 --> 00:20:16.805
- [Rip] Come on. boys.
- Mm.

343
00:20:16.908 --> 00:20:18.943
- [cowboy] Easy work.
- [Zach] Boy.

344
00:20:19.046 --> 00:20:21.356
Let an old man teach you. boy.

345
00:20:22.460 --> 00:20:24.115
[Beth]
<i>Well. sourcing your kitchens</i>

346
00:20:24.218 --> 00:20:26.529
from all over the West
is bad business.

347
00:20:26.667 --> 00:20:28.736
It's a constant back-and-forth.

348
00:20:28.805 --> 00:20:31.874
Ranchers. feedlots. packers.

349
00:20:32.012 --> 00:20:34.598
It's a lot of middlemen. and
I know 'cause I'm one of 'em.

350
00:20:34.667 --> 00:20:36.770
If you have
a license with 10-Petal Steaks.

351
00:20:36.839 --> 00:20:38.494
you get to cut
all that bullshit out.

352
00:20:38.632 --> 00:20:41.184
And the margins are so volatile.
it's like bleeding cash.

353
00:20:41.322 --> 00:20:42.839
And I don't know
about you. Zane.

354
00:20:42.943 --> 00:20:44.494
but I fucking hate overpaying.

355
00:20:44.598 --> 00:20:47.563
We have the highest-quality
Angus.

356
00:20:47.667 --> 00:20:50.529
bred. fed and finished in-house.

357
00:20:50.667 --> 00:20:52.150
We're one of the few operations

358
00:20:52.253 --> 00:20:55.115
that has its own
USDA-approved slaughterhouse.

359
00:20:55.184 --> 00:20:56.874
It is a resource so coveted.

360
00:20:56.977 --> 00:20:59.563
even I couldn't
get on the schedule.

361
00:21:00.494 --> 00:21:02.322
Well. you've assumed
what I need.

362
00:21:02.425 --> 00:21:04.081
but why do I need it from you?

363
00:21:04.184 --> 00:21:06.253
The people
who dine in your restaurants.

364
00:21:06.391 --> 00:21:08.287
they don't pay top dollar

365
00:21:08.391 --> 00:21:09.701
just for a steak. right?

366
00:21:10.770 --> 00:21:13.287
You know. they want a story.

367
00:21:13.391 --> 00:21:15.115
They want an experience.

368
00:21:15.218 --> 00:21:17.012
We can give them that. a story.

369
00:21:17.081 --> 00:21:19.287
an authentic cowboy story.

370
00:21:19.391 --> 00:21:21.184
At 10-Petal.

371
00:21:21.287 --> 00:21:22.598
it is unlike any other.

372
00:21:22.701 --> 00:21:25.218
and we're here
to offer you first look.

373
00:21:25.322 --> 00:21:27.943
Well. that's... generous.

374
00:21:29.736 --> 00:21:30.908
You know. I walked this deal

375
00:21:31.046 --> 00:21:33.115
into your office
for a reason. Zane.

376
00:21:33.253 --> 00:21:35.287
Deals like this walk into
my office all the time.

377
00:21:35.391 --> 00:21:39.425
but money talks
and bullshit walks.

378
00:21:39.529 --> 00:21:40.874
Well. we're still sat.

379
00:21:40.943 --> 00:21:42.253
- aren't we?
- True.

380
00:21:42.356 --> 00:21:43.494
and I've never had a Dutton

381
00:21:43.598 --> 00:21:45.805
- sitting across my desk.
- Or a Jackson.

382
00:21:46.598 --> 00:21:50.322
Your father was a legend. Beth.

383
00:21:53.460 --> 00:21:55.150
McChesney spurs.

384
00:21:58.046 --> 00:21:59.632
They're beautiful.

385
00:22:00.598 --> 00:22:02.632
Worn. but not for a long time.

386
00:22:02.701 --> 00:22:04.563
[Zane] They were worn
by the Duke himself

387
00:22:04.632 --> 00:22:06.150
in <i>The Searchers.</i>

388
00:22:06.253 --> 00:22:09.150
My parents worked
nights and weekends.

389
00:22:10.391 --> 00:22:13.012
Double features at The Music Box
became my babysitter.

390
00:22:13.115 --> 00:22:16.943
The screen.
my escape from the city

391
00:22:17.046 --> 00:22:19.184
and John Wayne. my guide.

392
00:22:19.287 --> 00:22:22.667
I loved cowboys. And outlaws.

393
00:22:22.805 --> 00:22:24.874
Clearly. you still do.

394
00:22:29.977 --> 00:22:32.150
Tell me about the Yellowstone.

395
00:22:35.770 --> 00:22:37.563
The Yellowstone
will be written about

396
00:22:37.667 --> 00:22:39.150
in the history books.

397
00:22:41.012 --> 00:22:42.770
But the 10-Petal
and the Jacksons.

398
00:22:42.874 --> 00:22:44.150
they're still at it.

399
00:22:44.253 --> 00:22:47.460
190 years.
they have been ranching.

400
00:22:48.667 --> 00:22:51.012
You know. they arrived here
as the Sullivans. right?

401
00:22:51.667 --> 00:22:53.667
Escaping famine in Ireland.

402
00:22:53.805 --> 00:22:55.356
[Beulah]
With dreams

403
00:22:55.460 --> 00:22:57.425
of full bellies and warm sun.

404
00:22:57.494 --> 00:22:59.460
Instead. we got thrown smack dab

405
00:22:59.563 --> 00:23:01.460
in the middle
of the Texas Revolution.

406
00:23:02.253 --> 00:23:05.356
My great-granddaddy's
great-granddaddy. Liam Sullivan.

407
00:23:05.460 --> 00:23:07.425
was dodging bullets
and herding cattle

408
00:23:07.563 --> 00:23:09.667
for the O'Connors in Refugio.

409
00:23:09.736 --> 00:23:11.977
He knew that if
the cholera didn't kill him.

410
00:23:12.081 --> 00:23:14.563
the Comanches or the war would.

411
00:23:14.667 --> 00:23:17.874
So. in the dead of night.

412
00:23:17.943 --> 00:23:20.494
battle raging on the horizon.
he rustled

413
00:23:20.563 --> 00:23:22.081
a mess of his boss's longhorns

414
00:23:22.184 --> 00:23:23.494
and drove them
to the Winter Garden.

415
00:23:23.598 --> 00:23:26.150
An outlaw.
he took the name Jackson

416
00:23:26.218 --> 00:23:27.908
from the whore he fled with.

417
00:23:28.046 --> 00:23:29.908
and never looked back.

418
00:23:30.012 --> 00:23:32.529
[laughs]

419
00:23:32.598 --> 00:23:34.494
Hell. John Ford
couldn't have dreamed that up.

420
00:23:34.563 --> 00:23:36.287
[laughs]

421
00:23:36.425 --> 00:23:40.115
John Ford visited our ranch
when I was just a little girl.

422
00:23:40.218 --> 00:23:41.425
[Zane]
Really?

423
00:23:41.529 --> 00:23:42.391
[Beulah]
Yeah.

424
00:23:42.460 --> 00:23:43.460
You know. the Jacksons.

425
00:23:43.598 --> 00:23:45.874
they. uh. they understood

426
00:23:45.943 --> 00:23:48.356
that knowing when
to walk away is just as valuable

427
00:23:48.460 --> 00:23:50.425
as knowing when to fight.

428
00:23:52.770 --> 00:23:54.460
We'll gladly walk away

429
00:23:54.598 --> 00:23:57.115
if you can't see
this opportunity.

430
00:23:57.218 --> 00:23:59.115
